properties.description: Reuters News reported that on December 15, 1993, Serb nationalists dynamited the remains of the Ferhat Pasha mosque in Banja Luka. Much of the 16th century Ottoman Islamic mosque, a United Nations cultural heritage monument, was levelled. The perpetrators removed the debris from the site to further erase it.

Reuters News and others reported that on November 9, 1993, Croatian forces shelled the Stari Most in Mostar. The bridge collapsed after incessant shelling. The structure linked predominantly Muslim and Croat communities and had been constructed in 16th century Ottoman Islamic style.

The St. Louis Post-Dispatch reported that on June 6, 1992, fighting between Serbian and Muslim forces damaged the Begova mosque in Sarajevo. The 16th century mosque, located in the old Turkish quarter, suffered two direct hits from artillery fire.

Reuters News reported that between April 6, 1992 and June 19, 1992, fighting between Serbian and Muslim and Croat forces damaged the Karadjozbeg mosque in Mostar. The mosque’s cupola and tall minaret were destroyed.
The Boston Globe reported that on August 5, 1992, Croatian forces destroyed a church in Odzak. A rocket launched by Croatians as they attacked the area damaged the structure.

Agence France-Presse reported that between April 6, 1992 and August 16, 1992, Serbian forces fired ammunition at the Ferhat Pasha mosque in Banja Luka. The 16th century Turkish mosque was reportedly raked with gunfire.

Reuters News reported that between April 6, 1992 and September 25, 1992, Serb forces destroyed the Aladza mosque in Foca. The mosque’s minaret and courtyard were both devastated. The once Muslim majority town became entirely Serb-dominated.

The Christian Science Monitor reported that between April 6, 1992 and November 30, 1992, Serb forces demolished a mosque in Bratunac with explosives. Serb forces often destroyed mosques in areas where they established control.

The Independent reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 18, 1992, Serb forces partly tore off the roof of the Mehmed Pasha mosque in Mostar with gunfire. The mosque dates to the 17th century.

The Independent reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 18, 1992, Serb forces damaged the Turkish towers on the sides of the Stari Most in Mostar with artillery fire. Pieces of masonry were ripped off of the 17th and 18th century towers, relics of the Ottoman empire.

The Independent reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 18, 1992, Serb forces damaged the Stari Most in Mostar with artillery fire. The northern parapet was destroyed and the entire bridge was scarred with bullet holes. The Islamic-style bridge links Muslim and Croat communities in Mostar.

USA Today reported that in May 1992, Serbian forces destroyed the St. Mary Catholic Church in Sarajevo with artillery fire. Serbs identify with Christian orthodoxy as opposed to Catholicism, which is associated with Croats.

The Austin American-Statesman reported that on January 27, 1993, Serb forces burned the Osman Pasha mosque in Trebinje. The perpetrators prevented Muslims from putting out the fire at the 300-year-old mosque. Serbs were reportedly resettled in the property of 4,000 Muslims expelled from Trebinje.
The Austin American-Statesman reported that on January 27, 1993, Serb forces burned a mosque in a village near Trebinje. Serb forces also pressured Trebinje Muslims to abandon their property.

Reuters News reported that between April 6, 1992 and February 22, 1993, unspecified actors bulldozed a mosque in Derventa. It was implied that Serb forces destroyed the mosque in their occupation of the town. They also expelled Muslims from the town.

The New York Times reported that on February 24, 1993, Serbian forces damaged a mosque in Sarajevo’s old town with artillery fire, killing 5 worshippers and wounding 20 others. 5 shells struck the mosque as worshippers gathered for evening prayers.

The Tampa Bay Times reported that between April 6, 1992 and February 24, 1993 unspecified forces set off explosives that damaged a mosque northwest of Sarajevo. The mosque was damaged during fighting between Serbs and Croats.

Reuters News reported that between April 6, 1992 and March 3, 1993, Serb forces fired bullets at mosques in Janja. The gunfire scarred the mosque minarets. The Muslims of Janja had declared their loyalty to the Serb republic at the beginning of the war.

BBC reported that between April 6, 1992 and March 18, 1993, Serb forces destroyed the 6 mosques in Bijeljina. This occupied area was crucial in establishing Serbian control over a strategic corridor in northern Bosnia.
USA Today reported that between March 14-25, 1993, Serb forces damaged the minaret of a mosque in Tekija with a tank. The mosque’s minaret was broken in half.

Los Angeles Daily News reported that between April 6, 1992 and April 4, 1993, Serb forces blew up a 150-year-old mosque in Bileca. Shops belonging to Muslims were destroyed, and the Muslim population was expelled.

The St. Louis Post-Dispatch reported that between April 6, 1992 and April 19, 1993, Serbian forces destroyed mosques in Foca. Serbian leaders reportedly ordered paramilitary units to cleanse the town of non-Serbs. Most other signs of Muslim culture were also destroyed.
The New York Times reported that on April 18, 1993, Croat forces detonated a car bomb outside a mosque in Vitez, killing 3 people. The mosque sustained considerable damage.
The Pantagraph Bloomington reported that between April 6, 1992 and May 5, 1993, unspecified forces destroyed a mosque in Han Pijesak. It was uncertain whether Serb forces were the perpetrators.

The Associated Press reported that in February 1993, Serb forces blew up a mosque in Nova Kasaba. The mosque was reduced to a heap of bricks. Serb forces also burned all of the houses belonging to Muslims so as to reportedly prevent their return.

The Financial Times reported that between April 6, 1992 and May 8, 1993, Serb forces damaged and destroyed mosques and churches in Sarajevo with artillery fire. The destruction of these centuries-old cultural sites occurred during the siege of Sarajevo.

The Guardian reported that on May 7, 1993, Serb forces blew up the Ferhat Pasha mosque in Banja Luka. The 16th century mosque is considered an exemplar of Ottoman Islamic architecture and was granted UNESCO protection. The perpetrators bulldozed the debris from the site to further erase memory of its existence.

The Guardian reported that on May 7, 1993, Serb forces blew up the Arnaudija mosque in Banja Luka. The Ottoman-style mosque dates to the 16th century. The debris from the blast was removed from the site to further erase memory of its existence.

The Austin American-Statesman reported that between May 2-9, 1993, Serb forces destroyed a mosque in Zepa, killing 10 people. The perpetrators also damaged several schools and a hospital in their attack on the Muslim enclave.

The Toronto Star reported that between April 6, 1992 and May 15, 1993, Serb forces destroyed the Oriental Institute in Sarajevo with phosphorous rockets. The institute’s collection of manuscripts, including 10th century Persian ones, were lost.
The Financial Times reported that between April 6, 1992 and May 17, 1993, Serb forces destroyed the mosques in Zvornik. Many Muslims had fled the town, located at Bosnia’s border with Serbia.
The Wall Street Journal reported that in April 1993, Serb forces destroyed a mosque in Janja. Janja was also ethnically cleansed of non-Serb populations during Serb occupation.
BBC reported that between April 6, 1992 and June 5, 1993, Muslim forces burned the Catholic church in Bresovsko. The burning of the church occurred during an attack on Kiseljak.
BBC reported that between April 6, 1992 and June 5, 1993, Muslim forces burned the Klarisa monastery near Kiseljak. The burning of the church occurred during an attack on Kiseljak.

The St. Louis Post-Dispatch reported that on June 12, 1993, Serb forces damaged a Muslim cemetery in Sarajevo, killing 8 people. Serb forces fired a mortar shell that struck the cemetery during the Siege of Sarajevo.

The Observer reported that in June 1993, Mujahideen extremists damaged the Guca Gora monastery in Travnik. The perpetrators destroyed the stained-glass windows, sprayed graffiti, and tore down crosses. The Bosnian Muslim army dissuaded the extremists from dynamiting the monastery.

The Globe and Mail reported that between April 6, 1992 and November 16, 1993, Serb forces destroyed the Vrbanjska mosque in Banja Luka. Serb forces levelled all 16 of the predominantly-Serb city’s mosques and often bulldozed the sites of debris.

The Globe and Mail reported that between April 6, 1992 and November 16, 1993, Serb forces destroyed the Hadzi Zulkifar mosque in Banja Luka. Serb forces levelled all 16 of the predominantly-Serb city’s mosques and often bulldozed the sites of debris.

The Globe and Mail reported that between April 6, 1992 and November 16, 1993, Serb forces destroyed the Gazanferija mosque in Banja Luka. Serb forces levelled all 16 of the predominantly-Serb city’s mosques and often bulldozed the sites of debris.

The Globe and Mail reported that between April 6, 1992 and November 16, 1993, Serb forces destroyed the Mehdi-Bega Imamovica mosque in Banja Luka. Serb forces levelled all 16 of the predominantly-Serb city’s mosques and often bulldozed the sites of debris.

The Globe and Mail reported that between April 6, 1992 and November 16, 1993, Serb forces destroyed the Jama mosque in Banja Luka. Serb forces levelled all 16 of the predominantly-Serb city’s mosques and often bulldozed the sites of debris.

The Globe and Mail reported that between April 6, 1992 and November 16, 1993, Serb forces destroyed the Behram-Efendijina mosque in Banja Luka. Serb forces levelled all 16 of the predominantly-Serb city’s mosques and often bulldozed the sites of debris.

The Globe and Mail reported that between April 6, 1992 and November 16, 1993, Serb forces destroyed the Grabska mosque in Banja Luka. Serb forces levelled all 16 of the predominantly-Serb city’s mosques and often bulldozed the sites of debris.

The Globe and Mail reported that between April 6, 1992 and November 16, 1993, Serb forces destroyed the Hadzi Kurd mosque in Banja Luka. Serb forces levelled all 16 of the predominantly-Serb city’s mosques and often bulldozed the sites of debris.

The Globe and Mail reported that between April 6, 1992 and November 16, 1993, Serb forces destroyed the Hadzi-Mustaj Pase Sokolovica mosque in Banja Luka. Serb forces levelled all 16 of the predominantly-Serb city’s mosques and often bulldozed the sites of debris.

The Globe and Mail reported that between April 6, 1992 and November 16, 1993, Serb forces destroyed the Dolacka mosque in Banja Luka. Serb forces levelled all 16 of the predominantly-Serb city’s mosques and often bulldozed the sites of debris.
The Globe and Mail reported that in February 1993, Serb forces destroyed the mosque in Bjelovac. The Serbs performed this act as they drove out the Muslims that had previously attacked them.

Reuters News reported that in September 8, 1993, Serb radicals blew up the Hadziperviz mosque in Banja Luka. The 17th century mosque was one of the final two mosques in the city, the other 14 already having been destroyed. Banja Luka was a Serb nationalist stronghold.

The New York Times reported that on November 13, 1993, Muslim forces burned the Church of the Assumption of the Blessed Virgin Mary in Scit. The burning of this church occurred after Croat forces burned 2 mosques and an Islamic monastery in Olavak.
The Globe and Mail reported that in December 1993, Serb forces blew up two Muslim cemeteries in Banja Luka. Bulldozers were used to desecrate the site and remove debris.

The Christian Science Monitor reported that in April 1992, Serb forces destroyed the Olympic Museum in Sarajevo through bombardment. The museum, remembering the 1984 Sarajevo Olympic Games, was housed in a 1903 neo-Baroque villa.

The Christian Science Monitor reported that on May 25, 1992, Serb forces destroyed Zetra Olympic Hall in Sarajevo through bombardment. The ice-skating stadium burned down as a result of the bombardment.

The Christian Science Monitor reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 31, 1992, Serb forces damaged the Skenderija sports center in Sarajevo. The center was used during the 1984 Sarajevo Olympic Games.
The Christian Science Monitor reported that in August 1993, Serb forces set the Mt. Bjelasnica sporting facilities on fire. These facilities were used during the 1984 Sarajevo Olympic Games.

properties.sitename: Saint Michael the Archangel Church (Stara Pravoslavna Crkva Sarajevo)
properties.description: The St. Louis Post-Dispatch reported that between April 6, 1992 and February 18, 1994, Serb forces struck the roof of the Church of St. Michael the Archangel in Sarajevo with a shell. The Serbian Orthodox church continued to operate throughout the war.

The Associated Press reported that between April 6, 1992 and March 7, 1994, unspecified actors shelled a church in Cifluk during fighting between Muslims and Croats. The church contained a makeshift hospital.

The Washington Post reported that between April 6, 1992 and March 15, 1994, unspecified actors destroyed a mosque in Zepce. The Catholic and Orthodox churches in the town were boarded up and did not sustain damage.

The Wall Street Journal reported that between April 6, 1992 and March 18, 1994, unspecified actors dug up the Asim Ferhatovic Hase Olympic Stadium in Sarajevo. The stadium, used during the 1984 Sarajevo Olympic Games, was converted into a graveyard for the city’s wartime dead.
Reuters News reported that between March 20-26 1994, Croat extremists blew up a mosque in Zepce. Bosnian Muslims had burned down several Croat homes in Travnik prior to the bombing.

Reuters News reported that between April 6, 1992 and March 31, 1994, unspecified actors damaged a Croatian Catholic church in Bugojno. In 1994, Croats and Muslims stopped fighting in the area and began to improve relations.

BBC reported that on April 27, 1994, unspecified forces blew up a mosque in Livno. Livno is a predominantly Croat city. The attack happened as Croats and Muslims made efforts to develop peace through the creation of a canton system in Bosnia.

Agence France-Presse reported that between April 6, 1992 and May 1, 1994, unspecified actors damaged the Serbian Orthodox Church of the Holy Resurrection in Sarajevo. Located near the Sarajevo front line, the church’s windows blew out due to shelling.

Reuters News reported that between April 6, 1992 and May 14, 1994, Serb forces damaged a mosque in Celic. Located in the only corridor linking Serb-held territories in Bosnia to the Serbian state, Celic was of interest to Serbs.

The Associated Press reported that on May 21, 1994, a mosque was destroyed in Divjak. Croats claimed that Muslims blew up the mosque to garner sympathy, while others asserted that Croats were responsible for its destruction. Muslims and Croats were planning to form a federation of their territories at the time.
BBC reported that on May 9, 1992, Serb forces destroyed the Franciscan monastery library in Mostar. Serbs associated the monastery with their Croat enemies.

Reuters News reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 31, 1992, Serb forces hit Crkva Svetog Jakova, a church, in Medjugorje with shells. Medjugorje is an important pilgrimage site for many Catholics due to its association with Virgin Mary apparitions.

The Austin American-Statesman reported that between April 6, 1992 and July 24, 1994, unspecified actors heavily damaged a 17th century mosque in Mostar with shelling. The damage occurred during fighting between Serb forces and Muslim and Croat forces.

The Straits Times reported that in July 1994, Malaysian United Nations troops chopped up and burned a Croatian cross in Sarajevo. It is uncertain whether the troops, tasked with protecting civilians and supporting humanitarian endeavors in Bosnia, actually perpetrated this act.

Reuters News reported that between April 6, 1992 and November 8, 1994, Serb forces destroyed the Hadžijusufova mosque in Donji Vakuf. The town was 50% Muslim at the start of the war, but only 30 Muslim families remained by the end of 1994.

The Wall Street Journal reported that between April 6, 1992 and November 9, 1994, unspecified actors destroyed the monument for the site of the Franz Ferdinand assassination in Sarajevo. The site marked Serbian nationalist Princip’s act. Princip was reportedly considered a hero in Sarajevo until the Bosnian War.
The Globe and Mail reported that on November 11, 1994, Serb forces heavily damaged a Roman Catholic church in Mostar, killing six children. The church was shelled during Serb bombardment of the town.

Reuters News reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 31, 1992, Serb forces fired shells and bullets at the Malkoc Alaj Begova mosque in Prusac, damaging the roof and minaret. Serbs commonly targeted mosques during the Bosnian War.

BBC reported that on December 7, 1994, Croatian and Bosnian Croat forces damaged the Serbian Orthodox Temple of Descent of the Holy Spirit on the Apostles church in Glamoc. The damage occurred during Croat shelling of the Serb town.

properties.sitename: Church of the Descent of the Holy Spirit
properties.description: BBC reported that between December 1, 1994 and December 19, 1994, Croatian forces razed the Church of the Descent of the Holy Spirit in Vrbica. The destruction occurred during a Croatian military offensive targeting Bosnian Serb areas.

properties.sitename: Church of the Ascension of the Virgin Mary
properties.description: BBC reported that between December 1, 1994 and December 19, 1994, Croatian forces razed the Church of the Ascent of the Virgin Mary in Gubin. The destruction occurred during a Croatian military offensive targeting Bosnian Serb areas.

BBC reported that between April 6, 1992 and April 11, 1995, Bosnian Serb forces destroyed a majority of mosques in territory controlled by the Pale regime. The Pale regime refers to the self-declared Serb republic in Bosnia. Non-Serb populations have been expelled from the territory or imprisoned.

Agence France-Presse reported that on April 13, 1995, Bosnian Serb forces fired a shell at a mosque in Hrasnica, rocking the building. Fighting between Bosnian Serbs and Muslims and Croats continued as Serbs refused to accept a partition plan.

Agence France-Presse reported that on May 7, 1995, Serb forces dynamited a Catholic church in Banja Luka, damaging the building beyond repair. Increased harassment of Bosnian Croats occurred after the Croatian offensive against Serbs and in response to Bosnian Serb leader Karadzic’s urging.

The Associated Press reported that on May 7, 1995, Bosnian Serb forces bombed a Roman Catholic church in Bihac. A local bishop believed that Serbs sought to eradicate the Catholic church’s presence in the area.

properties.sitename: Church of St. Anthony of Padua
properties.description: The Associated Press reported that on May 7, 1995, Bosnian Serbs damaged the St. Anthony of Padua monastery in Sarajevo. Fires spread to the buildings, including a 300-year-old library, after the adjacent church was dynamited. The destruction occurred as Serbs began to beat and harass Catholic Croats in the area.

Agence France-Presse reported that on April 16, 1993, the Croat militia burned down two mosques in Ahmici. The Croat forces also massacred 114 Muslims in the village and burned down an additional 176 Muslim-owned buildings.

Reuters News reported that on May 12, 1995 Serb forces mined and burned the Saint Theresa church near Banja Luka, killing a priest and nun. Serbs began to target Croat Catholic churches after the successful Croatian offensive against them.

Reuters News reported that on May 15, 1995, Serb extremists blew up a Catholic bell tower in Motike. Serbs began to target Croat Catholic churches after the successful Croatian offensive ousted Serbs from their former areas of control. Croats are the minority population in the area.

Reuters News reported that on May 17, 1995, armed Serbs blew up a Roman Catholic church in a village near Banja Luka. A priest and two nuns were beaten by the perpetrators. Similar attacks on Croat Catholic property increased as Croatian forces retook Serb-held territory in northern Bosnia.

The National Catholic Reporter reported that on May 4, 1995, Serb forces fired upon several churches in the Banja Luka region. The perpetrators also bombed aid designated for Catholic Croats after the Croatian offensive ousted Serbs from their previously-held territories.

Agence France-Presse reported that on June 6, 1995, Serb forces blew up the Gradska mosque in Prnjavor. Bosnian Serb forces also expelled 400 Muslims through their homes in a continuation of their campaign of ethnic cleansing against non-Serbs in northern Bosnia.

The Boston Globe reported that between April 6, 1992 and June 25, 1995, Serb shelling and street fighting between Croats and Muslims damaged the mosques in Travnik. Travnik was the Ottoman capital of Bosnia and thus represents Bosnia’s Islamic traditions.
Reuters News reported that on June 25, 1995, Bosnian Serbs damaged a mosque in Butmir. The mosque’s minaret was toppled by artillery fire as the Siege of Sarajevo continued.

BBC reported that between July 11-14, 1995, Serb forces burned down the mosque in Potocari. The burning of the mosque was concurrent with the perpetration of the massacre against Bosnian Muslims in Srebrenica, Potocari’s municipality.

BBC reported that between 11-14, 1995, Serb forces burned down a mosque in Bajramovici. The burning of the mosque was concurrent with the perpetration of the massacre against Bosnian Muslims in Srebrenica, Potocari’s municipality.

The Washington Post reported that on July 25, 1995, Bosnian Serb forces damaged a 16th century mosque in Zepa. The perpetrators burned down the Bosnian Muslim enclave, a United Nations designated safe area, and expelled 4,500 civilians from it.

The Washington Post reported that on July 25, 1995, Bosnian Serb forces damaged an Ottoman empire-era stone tower in Zepa. The perpetrators burned down the Bosnian Muslim enclave, a United Nations designated safe area, and expelled 4,500 civilians from it.

properties.sitename: Sanski Most mosques-Sultan Mehmed Fatihova Mosque
properties.description: Deseret News reported that between May 25-28 1992, Serbs burned all 42 mosques in Sanski Most. The Serb perpetrators also arrested prominent Muslims from Sanski Most and destroyed the Muslim quarter of the town, burning hundreds of houses. Military operations did not occur in this area.

The Times reported that between May 1, 1992 and August 17, 1995, Serb forces burned down the mosques in Donji Vakuf. A majority of the town’s Muslims fled before Serbs occupied the ethnically-diverse area. Muslim residents expressed that it would be impossible to maintain an ethnic mix after the devastation of war and occupation.

The Evening Standard reported that between April 6, 1992 and September 18, 1995, unspecified actors damaged the  Orthodox Church of the Assumption of the Most Holy Theotokos in Donji Vakuf. The church’s pulpit was tipped over, and documents and vestments were scattered throughout the building. The Bosnian Army had captured the Serbian stronghold in 1995.

Agence France-Presse reported that between April 6, 1992 and September 20, 1995, unspecified actors destroyed a mosque in Bosanska Krupa. The town was predominantly Muslim at the start of the war. Serb forces were known to target mosques in areas of their control.

Agence France-Presse reported that between April 6, 1992 and September 20, 1995, unspecified actors destroyed the Croat Roman Catholic Church of the Blessed Virgin Mary in Bosanska Krupa. Croats comprised a minority of the town’s population at the start of the war. Serb forces were known to target Croat churches after the Croatian army’s expulsion of rebel serbs from Croatia.

Agence France-Presse reported that between April 6, 1992 and September 20, 1995, unspecified actors damaged the Orthodox Templf of Nativity of the Most Holy Mother of God in Bosanska Krupa. The church suffered broken windows, likely during the fighting as Serbs seized the town in 1992.
The Times reported that in 1992, Serb forces damaged the Gradska mosque in Kljuc. The mosque was reportedly shattered. Kljuc was the site of Serb-led ethnic cleansing against Bosnian Muslims.

The Independent reported that between April 6, 1992 and November 5, 1995, unspecified actors systematically destroyed every book in the children’s library in Mostar. Mostar was a site of conflict between Bosnian Serb, Muslim, and Croat forces throughout the Bosnian War.

The Independent reported that between April 6, 1992 and November 5, 1995, unspecified actors destroyed the printing works in Mostar twice, preventing the printing of death notices and cultural resources. Mostar was a site of conflict between Bosnian Serb, Muslim, and Croat forces throughout the Bosnian War.

Reuters News reported that between November 15-29, 1995, unspecified actors blew up a Serb Orthodox church near Sipovo. Bosnian Croat forces were suspected to be responsible for the destruction, given their looting of Serb property in the area.

The Associated Press reported that in 1993, Serb forces leveled the mosque in Rajska, reducing it to rubble. The Serbs systematically sacked and burned buildings during their retreat from the town. Rajska is located in an area crucial to the establishment of a Serb corridor to the west.
Reuters News reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, Serb paramilitaries demolished the Gradska mosque in Odzak. The perpetrators snapped the mosque’s minaret in half.

The Charleston Gazette reported that on December 25, 1995, Croats fired at mosques on the Muslim side of Mostar. The gunfire was reportedly celebratory. Muslim policeman were also wounded by Croat gunfire in the divided city.

The Star-Tribune reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, Serbs dynamited and razed almost all the Catholic churches in the Banja Luka area. Banja Luka was the site of a major ethnic cleansing operation targeting non-Serb populations.
The Boston Globe reported that in 1993, Serbs damaged the Roman Catholic Church of the Immaculate Conception in Dubrave. The perpetrators blew off the church’s roof, cupola, and cross.

Reuters News reported that between July 11-22, 1995, Serb forces destroyed a mosque in Srebrenica. The perpetrators toppled the mosque’s tower and shattered its dome. Srebrenica was the site of a major ethnic cleansing operation targeting Bosnian Muslims.

BBC reported that between January 1-25, 1996, unspecified actors desecrated Muslim graves in Priboj. Several murders, abductions, arson, and burglary also reportedly occurred in the area, leading Bosnian Muslims to leave temporarily.

properties.sitename: Mostar mosque next to Bosnian Muslim checkpoint
properties.description: The Boston Globe reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, unspecified actors destroyed a mosque in Mostar. The perpetrators collapsed the mosque’s dome and snapped its minaret.

The New York Times reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, unspecified actors blew off the roof of a Catholic church in Tuzla. The perpetrators also damaged the church’s Cubist religious murals.

BBC reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, Bosnian Croats destroyed the Bosnian Muslim International artist colony in Pocitelj. The perpetrators looted 800 works of art and planted crosses throughout the area.

The New York Times reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, Bosnian Serb forces destroyed ancient mosques and landmarks in Sarajevo. The shelling of these cultural sites occurred during the Siege of Sarajevo.

BBC reported that between November 8, 1995 and March 8, 1996, the Croatian army blew up the Serb Orthodox church of Vasily Ostroski in Blagaj. The Croatian army also burned down a majority of residential buildings and blew up the priest’s home during its five-month-long occupation of this area.

The Boston Globe reported that between July 11, 1995 and July 22, 1995, Serb forces destroyed two mosques in Srebrenica. The destruction of these mosques was concurrent with the massacre of approximately 8,000 Bosnian Muslim men and boys in the town. Those massacred were buried in mass graves.

BBC reported that between January 1, 1996 and June 25, 1996, Croat authorities destroyed the museum town of Pocitelj.  Pocitelj dates to the 14th century and remembers several important phases of Bosnian history.

BBC reported that between June 1, 1996 and June 25, 1996, unspecified actors destroyed Islamic religious community buildings in Busovaca. This area was under Croat control at the time of the destruction.

BBC reported that between June 1, 1996 and June 25, 1996, unspecified actors destroyed Islamic religious community buildings in Vitez. This area was under Croat control at the time of the destruction.

Reuters News reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, unspecified actors destroyed the mosque in Aliscici. The town’s Muslim settlement also sustained considerable damage during the war.

The Pittsburgh Post-Gazette reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, Serbs destroyed three old mosques in Visegrad. The mosques were reportedly damaged so thoroughly that vegetation will erase any discernible trace of them.

The Globe and Mail reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, Serbs destroyed all the mosques in Doboj. The Muslim population of the area reportedly dropped significantly by the end of the war.
BBC reported that on September 20, 1996, Muslims damaged the Pokojiste Catholic cemetery. The perpetrators desecrated 20 headstones, broke all of the stone urns, and smashed the cemetery gates.

BBC reported that between September 20, 1996 and October 2, 1996, unspecified actors desecrated the Croat Catholic cemetery in Brajkovici. The granite gravestones were reportedly removed from the graves in the cemetery. Brajkovici was controlled by the Army of Bosnia-Herzegovina at the time of destruction.

BBC reported that between September 20, 1996 and October 2, 1996, unspecified actors desecrated the Croat Catholic cemetery in Slimena. The granite gravestones were reportedly removed from the graves in the cemetery. Slimena was controlled by the Army of Bosnia-Herzegovina at the time of destruction.

BBC reported that between September 20, 1996 and October 2, 1996, unspecified actors desecrated the Croat Catholic cemetery in Guca Gora. The granite gravestones were reportedly removed from the graves in the cemetery. Guca Gora was controlled by the Army of Bosnia-Herzegovina at the time of destruction.

BBC reported that between September 20, 1996 and October 2, 1996, unspecified actors desecrated the Croat Catholic cemetery in Gostunj. The granite gravestones were reportedly removed from the graves in the cemetery. Gostunj was controlled by the Army of Bosnia-Herzegovina at the time of destruction.

BBC reported that between July 10-15, 1992, Bosnian Serbs set aflame the mosque in Biljani. All houses in the town were also set on fire, and approximately 300 people were killed or arrested during the Serb attack.
Reuters News reported that in May 1992, unspecified actors destroyed the mosque in Memici. The mosque sustained heavy shelling.

Agence France-Presse reported that on October 17, 1996, Serbs bulldozed the final traces of the Ferhadija mosque in Banja Luka. The historic mosque had originally been blown up in 1993. Bulldozing the remains of the site was reportedly an attempt to intimidate Muslim deputies before a parliament session.

Reuters News reported that between January 1, 1992 and April 6, 1992, unspecified actors attacked the Serb Orthodox St. Peter and Paul church in Kozarac. The church was reportedly attacked as tensions developed prior to the start of the Bosnian War.

Reuters News reported that between October 20-26, 1996, Serb forces systematically destroyed two mosques in Prijedor. 90 houses belonging to Muslims were also destroyed. Such ethnically-targeted destruction became increasingly prevalent as refugees prepared to return to their ethnically-mixed towns.
BBC reported that between November 1-6, 1996, Islamic fundamentalists destroyed the Catholic graveyard in Mir. The Mir Catholic graveyard had also suffered damage in June 1996.
BBC reported that on November 3, 1996, Muslim army soldiers damaged the Catholic graveyard in Bijelo Borje. The soldiers reportedly destroyed several tombstones.

BBC reported that between November 1-6, 1996, Muslim extremists bombed the Sveti Ivo monastery near Capljina. The bombing occurred as part of a series of attacks targeting Catholic religious sites throughout Bosnia.

BBC reported that between November 1-6, 1996, Muslim extremists bombed the Guca Gora monastery near Travnik. The bombing occurred as part of a series of attacks targeting Catholic religious sites throughout Bosnia.

BBC reported that between November 1-6, 1996, Muslims damaged the Catholic graveyard in Bugojno. The perpetrators reportedly received permission from local authorities to destroy headstones in the cemetery. The desecration occurred as part of a series of attacks targeting Catholic religious sites throughout Bosnia.

The Independent reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, unspecified actors destroyed the Aers Aevi Museum of Contemporary Arts in Sarajevo. The museum and its substantial library likely suffered heavy losses due to Serb shelling during the Siege of Sarajevo.

The Austin American-Statesman reported that in October 1996, Bosnian Serbs destroyed two mosques in Banja Luka. The Serb perpetrators also burned down 80 homes that had been abandoned by Muslims during the war.

BBC reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, the Bosnian government army damaged, looted, and destroyed Serb Orthodox churches in Kakanj. Bosnian President Izetbegovic reportedly ordered the systematic destruction of these buildings.

BBC reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, the Bosnian government army damaged, looted, and destroyed Serb Orthodox churches in Turbe. Bosnian President Izetbegovic reportedly ordered the systematic destruction of these buildings.

BBC reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, the Bosnian government army damaged, looted, and destroyed Serb Orthodox churches in Zenica. Bosnian President Izetbegovic reportedly ordered the systematic destruction of these buildings.

properties.sitename: Serb orthodox churches in Golo Brdo
properties.description: BBC reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, the Bosnian government army damaged, looted, and destroyed Serb Orthodox churches in Golo Brdo. Bosnian President Izetbegovic reportedly ordered the systematic destruction of these buildings.

BBC reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, the Bosnian government army damaged, looted, and destroyed Serb Orthodox churches in Visoko. Bosnian President Izetbegovic reportedly ordered the systematic destruction of these buildings.

BBC reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, the Bosnian government army damaged, looted, and destroyed Serb Orthodox churches in Blagaj. Bosnian President Izetbegovic reportedly ordered the systematic destruction of these buildings.

BBC reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, the Bosnian government army damaged, looted, and destroyed Serb Orthodox churches in Sitnik. Bosnian President Izetbegovic reportedly ordered the systematic destruction of these buildings.

BBC reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, the Bosnian government army damaged, looted, and destroyed Serb Orthodox churches in Konjic. Bosnian President Izetbegovic reportedly ordered the systematic destruction of these buildings.

BBC reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, the Bosnian government army damaged, looted, and destroyed Serb Orthodox churches in Puracic. Bosnian President Izetbegovic reportedly ordered the systematic destruction of these buildings.
