properties.description: BBC reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, the Bosnian government army damaged, looted, and destroyed Serb Orthodox churches in Jeginov Lug. Bosnian President Izetbegovic reportedly ordered the systematic destruction of these buildings.

BBC reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, the Bosnian government army damaged, looted, and destroyed Serb Orthodox churches in Pozarnica. Bosnian President Izetbegovic reportedly ordered the systematic destruction of these buildings.

BBC reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, the Bosnian government army damaged, looted, and destroyed Serb Orthodox churches in Dubnica. Bosnian President Izetbegovic reportedly ordered the systematic destruction of these buildings.

BBC reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, the Bosnian government army damaged, looted, and destroyed Serb Orthodox churches in Blatnica. Bosnian President Izetbegovic reportedly ordered the systematic destruction of these buildings.

BBC reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, the Bosnian government army damaged, looted, and destroyed Serb Orthodox churches in Zlijebac. Bosnian President Izetbegovic reportedly ordered the systematic destruction of these buildings.

BBC reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, the Bosnian government army damaged, looted, and destroyed Serb Orthodox churches in Fakovici. Bosnian President Izetbegovic reportedly ordered the systematic destruction of these buildings.

BBC reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, the Bosnian government army destroyed the Serb Orthodox church of the Most Holy Theotokos in Srebrenica Bosnian President Izetbegovic reportedly ordered the systematic destruction of these buildings.

BBC reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, the Bosnian government army destroyed and burned down the Serb Orthodox church of the Prophet St. Elijah in Gradacac. Bosnian President Izetbegovic reportedly ordered the systematic destruction of these buildings.

Reuters News reported that on November 25, 1996, unspecified actors knocked down the wooden fence of St. Michael’s Catholic Church in Vares. The church is the oldest preserved Catholic church in Bosnia and dates to the 17th century.

The Pantagraph Bloomington reported that between July 11, 1995 and December 2, 1996, unspecified actors tampered with four mass graves in the Srebrenica area. Bodies were reportedly removed from the graves in order to conceal evidence of war crimes committed against Bosnian Muslims.

Agence France-Presse reported that between February 9-16, 1997, unspecified actors desecrated several graves at the Catholic cemetery in Klopce. Klopce is located in a Bosnian Muslim administered canton of the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina.

properties.sitename: Gornji Banjevac St. Elijah Catholic church
properties.description: BBC reported that on February 17, 1997, unspecified actors blew up the St. Elijah Catholic Church in Gornji Banjevac. The bombing blew the roof off the church and set fire to it, also fomenting unease among Croats in the Muslim-administered region.

properties.sitename: Church of St. Anthony of Padua
properties.description: Reuters News reported that on February 18, 1997, unspecified actors stoned and bombed St. Anthony’s Catholic Church in Sarajevo. The destruction occurred as part of a series of attacks targeting Catholic religious sites in Muslim administered areas throughout Bosnia.

properties.sitename: Donji Vakuf Saint Theresa's Catholic Church
properties.description: Reuters News reported that on February 25, 1995, unspecified forces dynamited Saint Theresa’s church in Donji Vakuf. The attack damaged the church’s stone wall and the chapel’s interior rooms and broke several windows. The attack occurred in a Muslim-controlled in the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina.

Reuters News reported that on March 3, 1997, unspecified actors bombed the Church of Saint Joseph in Sarajevo. The bombing was one of several attacks on Catholic churches in Bosnia as Pope John Paul II prepared to visit Sarajevo.

Reuters News reported that on March 15, 1997, unspecified actors bombed a mosque in Stipanici. The Stipanici mosque was the only remaining Islamic place of worship in the Croat-held region. The bombing was part of a series of attacks on mosques and churches in the Bosnian federation.

BBC reported that on March 20, 1997, unspecified actors bombed the Catholic parish church in Donje Puticevo, destroying the belfry and damaging the church’s interior. Donje Puticevo was a majority Croat town prior to the Bosnian War, but became inhabited by Muslims after it.

BBC reported that on March 20, 1997, a terrorist group bombed St. Mary’s Heart Catholic church in Humac, destroying the belfry and substantially damaging the church. Humac is located in an area controlled by Bosnian Muslims.

Reuters News reported that on March 28, 1997, unspecified actors launched a grenade at a mosque in Livno. Tensions between Croats and Muslims were reportedly high in the jointly-administered federation after Croats prevented Muslims from visiting a cemetery in Mostar.

properties.sitename: Sarajevo/central Bosnia 5 Roman catholic churches and 2 mosques
properties.description: The Cincinnati Post reported that in March 1997, unspecified actors bombed five Catholic churches and two mosques in Sarajevo. The increased frequency of attacks on religious sites is attributed to the pope’s anticipated visit to Bosnia.

The Times reported that on April 5, 1997, unspecified actors fired three grenades at a Franciscan friary near Kakanj. 40 windows were smashed in the friary which is one of Bosnia’s oldest religious buildings. There were several attacks on mosques and Catholic churches throughout Bosnia between February and April 1997.

The Times reported that between March 8, 1997 and April 8, 1997, three Catholic churches and two mosques were damaged in Bosnia. The retaliatory attacks occurred as Pope John Paul II’s visit to Sarajevo grew closer.

Agence France-Presse reported that between April 6, 1994 and December 14, 1995, Serbs destroyed the Atik mosque and its cemetery in Koraj. Mosques located in areas under Serb-control during the Bosnian War were often targeted in conjunction with ethnic cleansing operations.

BBC reported that between April 14-21, 1997, unspecified actors fired a rocket at a mosque in Grborezi. A house belonging to Bosnian Muslims in the same area also suffered gunfire. Grborezi is located in a Croat-controlled canton of the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina.

The New York Times reported that in 1992, Serb forces dynamited a mosque in Brcko. The perpetrators also removed all traces of rubble from the site to completely erase the structure. Muslims had fled from the town as fighting began in 1992.

Reuters News reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 31, 1992, Croatian Defence Council troops dynamited a mosque in Lasva Valley. The valley was the site of an ethnic purge that killed hundreds of Muslims and destroyed their homes and property.

Reuters News reported that on September 3, 1997, unspecified actors bombed the Roman Catholic Saint Ignacije center in Bosnia, causing significant damage. There were several attacks on religious sites and centers throughout Bosnia after the establishment of the Bosnian federation.

Reuters News reported that on September 25, 1997, unspecified actors bombed the Dzudza Dzafer mosque in Tomislavgrad, substantially damaging its shrine and library. The 17th century mosque is a national monument of Bosnia and Herzegovina.

The Christian Science Monitor reported that in 1993, Serbs damaged the Serb Orthodox Church in Tuzla with a shell. The church is one of the few Serb Orthodox churches in the region that has not suffered defilement or desecration in the wake of the Bosnian War.
USA Today reported that in September 1997, Serbs demolished a mosque in Memici. The perpetrators reportedly destroyed the mosque in order to discourage the return of Muslims to the area.

Dow Jones News Service reported that on October 27, 1997, unspecified actors bombed a Serb Orthodox church under construction in Brcko. Muslims had objected to the construction of the church as they returned after the war’s end.

The Times reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, unspecified actors damaged the Mostar University library. Mostar was a site of sustained fighting between Bosnian Muslims, Croats, and Serbs during the Bosnian War.

properties.sitename: Sarajevo western suburb Roman Catholic church
properties.description: Reuters News reported that on December 19, 1997, unspecified actors planted an explosive device at a Roman Catholic church in a western Sarajevo suburb. Police discovered the device before it detonated.

Agence France-Presse reported that on December 26, 1997, unspecified actors desecrated a Muslim cemetery in Mostar. The perpetrators vandalized 30 gravestones. The cemetery is located in the Croat part of the town.

BBC reported that between December 23-28, 1997, unspecified actors razed the memorial building of the central mosque in Modrica, a Serb-administered town. The destruction of this building reportedly completed the erasure of Islamic culture in the town.

IPR Strategic Information Database reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, unspecified actors damaged a mosque in the Chakarliyeh village. Serb forces often targeted mosques in their ethnic cleansing campaigns throughout Bosnia.

BBC reported that between February 1-24, 1998, unspecified actors damaged the Catholic parish church in Lovnica. The perpetrators removed the bell and roof from the church. Lovnica is located in a canton jointly-administered by Croats and Bosnian Muslims.

Reuters News reported that between December 14, 1995 and March 4, 1998, Croats destroyed a mosque in Stolac. Croats reportedly destroyed the Muslim neighborhood, including houses, to prevent the return of refugees as guaranteed by the Dayton Accord.
BBC reported that on April 6, 1998, unspecified actors destroyed the Zviza Catholic cemetery in Poculica.The perpetrators broke and desecrated gravestones and set the cemetery chapel on fire.

The Associated Press reported that between July 22, 1995 and April 22, 1998, unspecified actors tampered with a mass grave in Brnica. The perpetrators likely removed bodies from the site in order to conceal evidence of atrocities committed against Bosnian Muslims.

Agence France-Presse reported that on April 23, 1998, Serbs set the Roman Catholic Church of St. George the Martyr in Derventa on fire. The attack occurred as approximately 40 worshippers gathered before a Bosnian Croat cardinal.
The Waterloo Region Record reported that between April 6, 1992 and May 9, 1998, unspecified actors blew up a church in Brcko. The city is located in the Serb-controlled Republika Srpska.

The Washington Post reported that in October 1996, Serbs felled the ancient trees flanking the site of the Ferhadija mosque in Banja Luka. The mosque had been destroyed in 1993 and its remains bulldozed in 1996 to erase any sign of its existence.

The Associated Press reported that between July 22, 1995 and May 13, 1998, unspecified actors tampered with a mass grave in Zvornik. The perpetrators likely removed bodies from the site in order to conceal evidence of atrocities committed against Bosnian Muslims.

BBC reported that on May 22, 1998, Croat youths removed a fence at the former site of the Esma Sultanamosque in Jajce. The fence memorialized the destroyed mosque. The perpetrators then converted the area into a parking space.

properties.sitename: Kakanj St. Peter and Paul Church
properties.description: Agence France-Presse reported that on July 29, 1998, unspecified actors bombed the Saint Peter and Paul Church in Kakanj. The blast shattered the church’s windows and damaged a significant part of its main wall. The church is located in a Muslim-controlled canton of the federation.

The International Herald Tribune reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, Serbs blew up or burned the 216 mosques in Serb-controlled Bosnia. Mosques were often destroyed during Serb-led campaigns of ethnic cleansing against Bosnian Muslims.

Agence France-Presse reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, Serbs destroyed the mosque in the town center of Klisa. Serbs expelled the entirely Muslim population from the town during the war and subsequently destroyed their homes and property.

The Independent reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, Serbs destroyed the mosque in Vlasenica. Serbs also expelled the 8,000 Muslims that populated the area during the war. The Muslim former residents had not returned to Vlasenica by 1998.

properties.sitename: St. George the Martry Catholic Church
properties.description: The National Catholic Reporter reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, unspecified actors damaged the St. George the Martry Catholic Church in Derventa, breaking its windows and ripping its door off. Most of the area’s Croats fled during the war and had not returned by 1998.

The Yorkshire Press reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 31, 1992, Serb forces destroyed the three mosques in Brcko. All of the town’s Muslim tradition was reportedly erased in Serb-led ethnic cleansing campaigns against non-Serb populations in the region.

NPR reported that in December 1994, residents of Sarajevo tore apart the Austria House in Sarajevo for firewood. The chalet, built for the 1984 Sarajevo Olympic Games and converted into an art gallery afterwards, was destroyed during the Siege of Sarajevo.

BBC reported that on April 17, 1999, unspecified actors threw a grenade at a mosque in Prozor, shattering the mosque’s windows and starting a small fire. The mosque is located in a Croat-administered town in western Bosnia.

NPR reported that in December 1994, residents of Sarajevo tore apart the Austria House in Sarajevo for firewood. The chalet, built for the 1984 Sarajevo Olympic Games and converted into an art gallery afterwards, was destroyed during the Siege of Sarajevo.

BBC reported that on April 17, 1999, unspecified actors threw a grenade at a mosque in Prozor, shattering the mosque’s windows and starting a small fire. The mosque is located in a Croat-administered town in western Bosnia.

The Wall Street Journal reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, Croat forces dynamited the Balanovats mosque in west Mostar. West Mostar is the predominantly Croat part of Mostar, and there was resistance from Croat authorities to rebuild the mosque after the war’s end.

NPR reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 31, 1992, unspecified actors destroyed the Symphony Hall in Sarajevo. The hall was destroyed during the Siege of Sarajevo, and likely sustained damage as a result of Serb shelling, like many other buildings in the city.

properties.sitename: Church of the Holy Trinity Mostar
properties.description: The Boston Globe reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, unspecified actors destroyed the Serbian Orthodox Church of the Holy Trinityin Mostar. The cathedral was reduced to rubble. Serbs are associated with Christian orthodoxy.

The Boston Globe reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, unspecified actors destroyed a riverside mosque in Mostar. Aggressors were reportedly attempting to destroy Bosnian Muslim heritage. The mosque was restored after the war.

Agence France-Presse reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, Bosnian Serb and Muslim forces damaged a Soviet-style mural commemorating World War II in a school in Sarajevo. Bosnian Muslims used the school as a military barracks and graffitied the mural. It was also damaged by Serb shelling.

HINA reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, unspecified actors damaged St. Luke’s Franciscan monastery in Serb-held Jajce. The monastery contains the remains of the last Bosnian king. Serbs are suspected to be responsible for damage to the Croat site.

The International Herald Tribune reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, unspecified actors destroyed the ancient Sisam Imbrahim-immersed mosque in Pocitelj. Pocitelj is a historic Ottoman town and is considered to be an open-air museum due to its Ottoman Islamic tradition.

BBC reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, unspecified actors burned 19 Bosnian Muslims to death in the mosque in Hanifici, damaging the mosque. Patterns of ethnic cleansing and mass grave burial suggest that Serb forces were responsible for the destruction.

Agence France-Presse reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, unspecified actors destroyed a mosque in Mostar. Mostar was the site of fighting between Bosnian Muslims, Croats, and Serbs during the war and suffered shelling and artillery fire.

HINA reported that on November 7, 1999, unspecified actors broke four windows and damaged the door of a Croat Catholic church in Bijela. The population of Bijela is majority Croat, and Bijela reportedly had the highest number of Croat refugee returns to their pre-war homes.

U.S. Newswire reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, Bosnian Serb forces damaged the Old Jewish Cemetery in Sarajevo with artillery fire and mining. The site was used as a Serb sniper post. The cemetery is the oldest intact Jewish burial ground in southeastern Europe.

The Associated Press reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, unspecified actors destroyed a Roman Catholic church in Derventa. When priests attempted to visit the ruins in the Serb-administered town in 1999, they were attacked.

The Associated Press reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, Serb forces demolished a mosque in a village near Omarska. Omarska contained a Serb-run concentration camp targeting non-Serb populations. The Serb destruction of mosques aligned with their ethnic cleansing designs.

The Associated Press reported that between July 11-22, 1995, Serb forces razed the main mosque in Srebrenica. The destruction of the mosque occurred as part of an ethnic cleansing campaign that killed approximately 7,500 Bosnian Muslim men and deported 25,000 women and children. Serbs sought control of the strategically-located town.

BBC reported that between January 1, 2000 and April 4, 2000, unspecified actors desecrated Croat Catholic graves in Kocine, near Mostar. Croats began to return to the area in 2000 and implied that Bosnian Muslims were responsible for the desecration.

Agence France-Presse reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, unspecified actors destroyed a Croat Catholic chapel in Derventa. The area was controlled by Serbs during the Bosnian War.

Agence France-Presse reported that on June 26, 2000, unspecified actors bombed a newly rebuilt Croat Catholic chapel in Derventa. The chapel was one of several Catholic sites targeted as Croats returned to their pre-war homes in the Serb-held area.

Pakistan Press International reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, enemies of Bosnian Muslims burned and destroyed a mosque near Sarajevo. More than 1,000 mosques were reportedly razed during the Bosnian War.

BBC reported that on August 8, 2000, unspecified actors threw a grenade at a Catholic church in Zasavica. The town is located in the Serb-administered Srpska Republic. Attacks on sites of Croat Catholic heritage became increasingly prevalent with the return of Croat refugees to their pre-war homes.

BBC reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, unspecified actors destroyed a mosque in Serb-administered Kozarac. Mosques were commonly destroyed during Serb-led campaigns of ethnic cleansing in Bosnia.

properties.sitename: Congregational Church of the Holy Mother
properties.description: BBC reported that between August 30, 2000 and September 6, 2000, unspecified actors looted the Serb Orthodox Congregational church of the Holy Mother in Bascarsija, Sarajevo. A deacon was also attacked. Sarajevo is located in a Bosnian Muslim-adminstered canton of the federation.

BBC reported that between August 30, 2000 and September 6, 2000, unspecified actors looted the Serb Old Orthodox church in Bascarsija, Sarajevo. A deacon was also attacked. Sarajevo is located in a Bosnian Muslim-adminstered canton of the federation.

Reuters News reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, Serb forces destroyed a mosque in Novoseoci. They buried the remains of the destroyed mosque alongside the remains of 50 Bosnian Muslims in a mass grave at the Ivan Polje meadow.

The New Straits Times reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, unspecified actors damaged the Gazi Husrev-beg mosque in Sarajevo. The Gazi Husrev-beg mosque is the largest historical mosque in Bosnia and testifies to its Ottoman past. The mosque was likely targeted by Serb shelling during the Siege of Sarajevo.

The Associated Press reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, Serb forces destroyed the local mosque in Foca. In an attempt to entirely erase signs of Muslim heritage, the rubble was even removed from the site. Most of the town’s Muslims fled the city due to Serb ethnic cleansing campaigns.

Agence France-Presse reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 31, 1992, Serb forces blew up a mosque in Foca. During the war, Foca was a Serb stronghold from which Bosnian Muslims populations fled or were expelled.

The Christian Science Monitor reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, Serb forces destroyed the neighborhood mosque in Prijedor. The houses located in the city’s Muslim old quarter were also destroyed. Serb forces killed approximately 3,000 Bosnian Muslims in the area.

BBC reported that on May 10, 1993, the Croat Defence Council destroyed the Baba Bashir mosque in Balinovac, Mostar. The Dayton Agreement established the area as Croat-administered, and Croats reportedly obstructed attempts to rebuild the mosque after the war.

BBC reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, unspecified actors destroyed five mosques in Mostar. Fighting between Bosnian Serbs, Muslims, and Croats occurred in the area, with shells often damaging sites.

BBC reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, unspecified actors destroyed the Salihbegovic dzamija mosque in Bijeljina. The mosque was likely destroyed by Serb forces in their occupation of the town.

BBC reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, unspecified actors destroyed the Dasnica mosque in Bijeljina. The mosque was likely destroyed by Serb forces in their occupation of the town.

BBC reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, unspecified actors destroyed the Krpic mosque in Bijeljina. The mosque was likely destroyed by Serb forces in their occupation of the town.
BBC reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, unspecified actors destroyed the Atih mosque in Janja. The mosque was likely destroyed by Serb forces in their occupation of the town.

BCC reported that on December 19, 2000, unspecified actors stoned a newly-built mosque in Obradovac, smashing several windows and damaging the facade. Obradovac is located in the Serb-administered municipality of Bosanska Gradiska. The post-war reconstruction of religious buildings was often contentious.

BBC reported that between December 31, 2000 and January 3, 2001, 70 mujahidin partly destroyed the community cultural center and mosque in Boncinja. The perpetrators had illegally seized Serb property. When ordered to leave as Serbs returned, they destroyed Serb property in addition to the center and mosque.

The New York Times reported that between December 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, Serb forces razed a mosque in Zvornik. Mosques were often destroyed during Serb campaigns of ethnic cleansing. After the war, a makeshift marketplace replaced the mosque.

Agence France-Presse reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, unspecified actors destroyed five mosques in Prnjavor. Mosques located in such Serb-administered towns were often targeted by Serb forces during their wartime campaigns of ethnic cleansing. Serb authorities did not respond to the Islamic community’s requests to rebuild the mosques.

BBC reported that between April 13-14, 2001, unspecified actors removed nine crosses from graves in a Croat Catholic graveyard in Jelah. The municipality is located in the Bosniak-administered Zenica-Doboj canton of the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina.

Reuters News reported that on April 24, 2001, unspecified actors smashed a statue of Draza Mihajlovic in Brcko. The World War II-era statue of the Serb war criminal, convicted of collaborating with Germany and perpetrating war crimes, was located in Republika Srpska.

BBC reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, unspecified actors destroyed the Heart of Jesus Catholic Church in Doboj. Bosnian Croats are associated with Catholicism. Places of worship were often targeted by all sides in the Bosnian War, although the participation of Serbs in such acts was particularly prevalent.

The Associated Press reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, unspecified actors destroyed ten mosques in Trebinje. It is likely that Serb forces destroyed these mosques, given patterns of ethnic cleansing in Serb-held wartime territories. In 2001, Serbs rioted at the reconstruction of one of these mosques.

The Associated Press reported that on May 7, 2001, a Bosnian Muslim threw a hand grenade at a Serbian Orthodox church in Sanski Most, causing minor damage. The attack was reportedly triggered by Serb nationalist riots during mosque reconstruction ceremonies in Republika Srpska.

BBC reported that on May 9, 2001, unspecified actors desecrated an Orthodox cemetery in Tuzla, damaging 15 tombstones and breaking several windows and doors. The desecration occurred in the Bosniak canton after anti-Muslim riots in neighbording Republika Srpska.

The Boston Globe reported that between January 1, 2001 and May 13, 2001, vandals defaced the crucifix of an Orthodox church in Kula Grad. The vandalization occurred as part of a series of multi-directional attacks against religious sites throughout Bosnia, triggered by Serb riots at the ceremony for a mosque’s reconstruction in Republika Srpska.

properties.sitename: Doboj Memorial Plaque to Serb Soliders
properties.description: Reuters News reported that between January 1, 2001 and May 13, 2001, unspecified actors damaged a memorial plaque to Serb soldiers killed during the Bosnian War in Doboj. The vandalization occurred as part of a series of multi-directional attacks against religious and cultural sites throughout Bosnia, triggered by Serb riots at the ceremony for a mosque’s reconstruction in Republika Srpska.

Reuters News reported that between May 13-14, 2001, unspecified actors vandalized an Orthodox and Catholic cemetery in Lukavac. The vandalization occurred as part of a series of multi-directional attacks against religious and cultural sites throughout Bosnia, triggered by Serb riots at the ceremony for a mosque’s reconstruction in Republika Srpska.

Reuters News reported that between May 13-14, 2001, unspecified actors vandalized an Orthodox and Catholic cemetery in Lukavac. The vandalization occurred as part of a series of multi-directional attacks against religious and cultural sites throughout Bosnia, triggered by Serb riots at the ceremony for a mosque’s reconstruction in Republika Srpska.

Reuters News reported that between May 11-14, 2001, unspecified actors damaged Muslims gravestones in a cemetery in Banja Luka. The vandalization occurred as part of a series of multi-directional attacks against religious and cultural sites throughout Bosnia, triggered by Serb riots at the ceremony for a mosque’s reconstruction in Republika Srpska.

Reuters News reported that in 2000, teenagers damaged gravestones in the Old Jewish Cemetery in Sarajevo. Established by Sephardic Jews during the Ottoman period, the 16th century cemetery is the oldest intact Jewish burial ground in southeastern Europe.

Reuters News reported that between May 14-15, 2001, unspecified actors damaged a Serb graveyard near Srebrenica. Srebrenica was the sight of the 1995 massacre of approximately 8,000 Bosnian Muslim men and expulsion of Bosnian Muslim women and children.

BBC reported that between May 25-26, 2001, unspecified actors fired shots at an Orthodox monastery in Vrba. Houses belonging to Serbs were also shot at. Vrba is located in a Croat-administered canton of the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina.

BBC reported that on May 31, 2001, unspecified actors desecrated a Croat Catholic cemetery in Bijeljina. Headstones were toppled over in the cemetery. The act occurred as part of a series of assaults on Catholic officials and attacks on Catholic facilities during the week of the Pentecost in Bosnia.

BBC reported that on December 16, 2001, unspecified actors desecrated a Muslim graveyard in Prnjavor, toppling 30 tombstones. The site was reportedly attacked due to the beginning of construction work on a nearby mosque.

Agence France-Presse reported that on September 18, 2002, unspecified actors bombed the Gradska mosque in Kljuc, destroying its minaret and damaging its roof. The attack was reportedly an attempt to ignite ethnic tensions and prevent the return of Bosnian Muslim refugees to the Serb-controlled area.

The Associated Press reported that on December 4, 2002, unspecified actors threw an explosive device at an Islamic community building in Prijedor. The attack was one of three instances in which the building was targeted as Bosnian Muslims refugees returned to the Serb-held area in 2002.

Agence France-Presse reported that on December 7, 2002, unspecified actors bombed a mosque in the center of Doboj, causing minor damage. The attack was the second of two incidents targeting Muslim places of worship in the Serb-controlled part of Bosnia.

BBC reported that on August 20, 2003, unspecified actors desecrated the St. Mihovil cemetery in Sarajevo. 19 tomb crosses and central crucifix suffered damage. The St. Mihovil cemetery was one of several Orthodox and Catholic cemeteries damaged in the Bosniak canton.

BBC reported that on August 20, 2003, unspecified actors desecrated the St. Joseph cemetery in Sarajevo. Both tombstones and crosses were vandalized. The St. Joseph cemetery was one of several Orthodox and Catholic cemeteries damaged in the Bosniak canton.

BBC reported that on August 20, 2003, unspecified actors desecrated the St. Mark cemetery in Sarajevo. Both tombstones and crosses were vandalized. The St. Mark cemetery was one of several Orthodox and Catholic cemeteries damaged in the Bosniak canton.

BBC reported that on August 20, 2003, unspecified actors desecrated the Lav cemetery in Sarajevo. Both tombstones and crosses were vandalized. The Lav cemetery was one of several Orthodox and Catholic cemeteries damaged in the Bosniak canton.

BBC reported that on November 23, 2003, unspecified actors fired bullets at a mosque in Cela. The mosque, which did not exist prior to the war, had been recently constructed as Bosnian Muslims returned to Republika Srpska.

The Associated Press reported that on March 18, 2004, unspecified actors set the roof of a Serb Orthodox church on fire in Bugojno, causing minor damage. The church is located in the Serb neighborhood of a predominantly Muslim town. The act occurred after the burning of Serb homes by Albanians in neighboring Kosovo.

BBC reported that between March 21-22, 1993, unspecified actors demolished the mosque in Orahova. Mosques in northern Bosnia were often destroyed by Serbs during campaigns of wartime ethnic cleansing in Serb-held territories.

BBC reported that on March 22, 2004, unspecified actors threw an explosive device at a newly reconstructed mosque in Orahova, damaging the facade and shattering glass. The damage occurred as Bosnian Muslim refugees began to return to the Serb-administered village.

Agence France-Presse reported that on October 18, 2004, two Bosnian Serbs damaged a mosque in Visegrad. The perpetrators destroyed part of a wall that was under construction in the Serb-administered town. The event occurred during Ramadan.

HINA reported that on May 5, 2005, unspecified actors desecrated the grave of a Catholic priest in Prijedor, breaking a wooden cross. Matanovic had been killed during the war after unknown perpetrators removed him from this home in the Serb-dominated city.

BBC reported that on May 6, 2005, unspecified actors damaged the city mosque’s Muslim cemetery in Prnjavor, desecrating 26 graves. It is suspected that the event was related to the commemoration of the Day of Mosques in the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina.

HINA reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, unspecified actors destroyed the Plehan Franciscan monastery near Derventa. 365 artifacts had been safely stored in the Archives of Republika Srpska during the war and were returned to the monastery in 2007.

The Associated Press reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, Serb forces destroyed two mosques in Konjevic Polje. The Bosnian Muslim population of the Serb-dominated area was expelled during the war, their property destroyed or appropriated by resettled Serbs.

Agence France-Presse reported that in 2010, unspecified actors damaged an Orthodox church in Rozanj. The perpetrators broke a window and forced the door in order to steal a generator and tools from the construction site of the church. Rozanj is located in the Muslim-Croat Federation of Bosnia.

Agence France-Presse reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, unspecified actors destroyed 23 mosques in and around Zvornik. Bosnian Serb forces expelled and massacred the Bosnian Muslim population from Zvornik during the Bosnian War.

Kuwait News Agency reported that between January 8-15, 2001, unspecified actors threw a molotov cocktail at an old mosque in Sarajevo. Several other mosques throughout Bosnia were the targets of arson attacks at this time.

HINA reported that on January 17, 2011, unspecified actors stoned the Trinity Catholic Church in Blagaj, smashing its windows. Destroyed during the Bosnian War, the church was declared a cultural monument in 2008 and subsequently reconstructed.

HINA reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, unspecified actors destroyed the Trinity Catholic Church in Blagaj. Local Catholic Croats had fled the area during the war. The site was stoned after its reconstruction in 2011.

BBC reported that between May 28-29, 2011, unspecified actors vandalized the Sefer Bey mosque in Banja Luka. The event is suspected to have been related to the arrest of Serb war criminal Ratko Mladic.

BBC reported that between May 29-30, 2011, unspecified actors stoned the newly renovated Old City mosque in Bosanska Dubica, damaging the front wall. Groups of people were reportedly chanting in support of Mladic outside of the town imam’s house.

BBC reported that between May 31, 2011 and June 3, 2011, unspecified actors vandalized the Serb Orthodox St. Sava temple in Blazuj, marking it with offensive graffiti. Blazuj is located in the Sarajevo canton of the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina, which is dominated by Bosnian Muslims.

BBC reported that between June 4-6, 2011, unspecified actors threw a hand grenade at a mosque in a village near Pale. The village is located in the Podrinje canton of the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina, which is dominated by Bosnian Muslims.

Reuters News reported that between May 13-14, 2001, unspecified actors vandalized an Orthodox and Catholic cemetery in Lukavac. The vandalization occurred as part of a series of multi-directional attacks against religious and cultural sites throughout Bosnia, triggered by Serb riots at the ceremony for a mosque’s reconstruction in Republika Srpska.

Reuters News reported that between May 13-14, 2001, unspecified actors vandalized an Orthodox and Catholic cemetery in Lukavac. The vandalization occurred as part of a series of multi-directional attacks against religious and cultural sites throughout Bosnia, triggered by Serb riots at the ceremony for a mosque’s reconstruction in Republika Srpska.

Reuters News reported that between May 11-14, 2001, unspecified actors damaged Muslims gravestones in a cemetery in Banja Luka. The vandalization occurred as part of a series of multi-directional attacks against religious and cultural sites throughout Bosnia, triggered by Serb riots at the ceremony for a mosque’s reconstruction in Republika Srpska.

Reuters News reported that in 2000, teenagers damaged gravestones in the Old Jewish Cemetery in Sarajevo. Established by Sephardic Jews during the Ottoman period, the 16th century cemetery is the oldest intact Jewish burial ground in southeastern Europe.

Reuters News reported that between May 14-15, 2001, unspecified actors damaged a Serb graveyard near Srebrenica. Srebrenica was the sight of the 1995 massacre of approximately 8,000 Bosnian Muslim men and expulsion of Bosnian Muslim women and children.

BBC reported that between May 25-26, 2001, unspecified actors fired shots at an Orthodox monastery in Vrba. Houses belonging to Serbs were also shot at. Vrba is located in a Croat-administered canton of the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina.

BBC reported that on May 31, 2001, unspecified actors desecrated a Croat Catholic cemetery in Bijeljina. Headstones were toppled over in the cemetery. The act occurred as part of a series of assaults on Catholic officials and attacks on Catholic facilities during the week of the Pentecost in Bosnia.

BBC reported that on December 16, 2001, unspecified actors desecrated a Muslim graveyard in Prnjavor, toppling 30 tombstones. The site was reportedly attacked due to the beginning of construction work on a nearby mosque.

Agence France-Presse reported that on September 18, 2002, unspecified actors bombed the Gradska mosque in Kljuc, destroying its minaret and damaging its roof. The attack was reportedly an attempt to ignite ethnic tensions and prevent the return of Bosnian Muslim refugees to the Serb-controlled area.

The Associated Press reported that on December 4, 2002, unspecified actors threw an explosive device at an Islamic community building in Prijedor. The attack was one of three instances in which the building was targeted as Bosnian Muslims refugees returned to the Serb-held area in 2002.

Agence France-Presse reported that on December 7, 2002, unspecified actors bombed a mosque in the center of Doboj, causing minor damage. The attack was the second of two incidents targeting Muslim places of worship in the Serb-controlled part of Bosnia.

BBC reported that on August 20, 2003, unspecified actors desecrated the St. Mihovil cemetery in Sarajevo. 19 tomb crosses and central crucifix suffered damage. The St. Mihovil cemetery was one of several Orthodox and Catholic cemeteries damaged in the Bosniak canton.

BBC reported that on August 20, 2003, unspecified actors desecrated the St. Joseph cemetery in Sarajevo. Both tombstones and crosses were vandalized. The St. Joseph cemetery was one of several Orthodox and Catholic cemeteries damaged in the Bosniak canton.

BBC reported that on August 20, 2003, unspecified actors desecrated the St. Mark cemetery in Sarajevo. Both tombstones and crosses were vandalized. The St. Mark cemetery was one of several Orthodox and Catholic cemeteries damaged in the Bosniak canton.

BBC reported that on August 20, 2003, unspecified actors desecrated the Lav cemetery in Sarajevo. Both tombstones and crosses were vandalized. The Lav cemetery was one of several Orthodox and Catholic cemeteries damaged in the Bosniak canton.

BBC reported that on November 23, 2003, unspecified actors fired bullets at a mosque in Cela. The mosque, which did not exist prior to the war, had been recently constructed as Bosnian Muslims returned to Republika Srpska.

The Associated Press reported that on March 18, 2004, unspecified actors set the roof of a Serb Orthodox church on fire in Bugojno, causing minor damage. The church is located in the Serb neighborhood of a predominantly Muslim town. The act occurred after the burning of Serb homes by Albanians in neighboring Kosovo.

BBC reported that between March 21-22, 1993, unspecified actors demolished the mosque in Orahova. Mosques in northern Bosnia were often destroyed by Serbs during campaigns of wartime ethnic cleansing in Serb-held territories.

BBC reported that on March 22, 2004, unspecified actors threw an explosive device at a newly reconstructed mosque in Orahova, damaging the facade and shattering glass. The damage occurred as Bosnian Muslim refugees began to return to the Serb-administered village.

Agence France-Presse reported that on October 18, 2004, two Bosnian Serbs damaged a mosque in Visegrad. The perpetrators destroyed part of a wall that was under construction in the Serb-administered town. The event occurred during Ramadan.

HINA reported that on May 5, 2005, unspecified actors desecrated the grave of a Catholic priest in Prijedor, breaking a wooden cross. Matanovic had been killed during the war after unknown perpetrators removed him from this home in the Serb-dominated city.

BBC reported that on May 6, 2005, unspecified actors damaged the city mosque’s Muslim cemetery in Prnjavor, desecrating 26 graves. It is suspected that the event was related to the commemoration of the Day of Mosques in the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina.

HINA reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, unspecified actors destroyed the Plehan Franciscan monastery near Derventa. 365 artifacts had been safely stored in the Archives of Republika Srpska during the war and were returned to the monastery in 2007.

The Associated Press reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, Serb forces destroyed two mosques in Konjevic Polje. The Bosnian Muslim population of the Serb-dominated area was expelled during the war, their property destroyed or appropriated by resettled Serbs.

Agence France-Presse reported that in 2010, unspecified actors damaged an Orthodox church in Rozanj. The perpetrators broke a window and forced the door in order to steal a generator and tools from the construction site of the church. Rozanj is located in the Muslim-Croat Federation of Bosnia.

Agence France-Presse reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, unspecified actors destroyed 23 mosques in and around Zvornik. Bosnian Serb forces expelled and massacred the Bosnian Muslim population from Zvornik during the Bosnian War.

Kuwait News Agency reported that between January 8-15, 2001, unspecified actors threw a molotov cocktail at an old mosque in Sarajevo. Several other mosques throughout Bosnia were the targets of arson attacks at this time.

HINA reported that on January 17, 2011, unspecified actors stoned the Trinity Catholic Church in Blagaj, smashing its windows. Destroyed during the Bosnian War, the church was declared a cultural monument in 2008 and subsequently reconstructed.

HINA reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, unspecified actors destroyed the Trinity Catholic Church in Blagaj. Local Catholic Croats had fled the area during the war. The site was stoned after its reconstruction in 2011.

BBC reported that between May 29-30, 2011, unspecified actors stoned the newly renovated Old City mosque in Bosanska Dubica, damaging the front wall. Groups of people were reportedly chanting in support of Mladic outside of the town imam’s house.

BBC reported that between May 31, 2011 and June 3, 2011, unspecified actors vandalized the Serb Orthodox St. Sava temple in Blazuj, marking it with offensive graffiti. Blazuj is located in the Sarajevo canton of the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina, which is dominated by Bosnian Muslims.

BBC reported that between June 4-6, 2011, unspecified actors threw a hand grenade at a mosque in a village near Pale. The village is located in the Podrinje canton of the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina, which is dominated by Bosnian Muslims.

The Irish Times reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, Croats blew up a monument to the Ustasa’s Serb victims in Surmanci. There existed tensions between Croats and Serbs in relation to the memorial site and its representation of World War II-era victimhood and perpetration.

BBC reported that between September 24-26, 2011, unspecified actors attacked the Sefer Bey mosque in Banja Luka. Considering the Serb destruction of all mosques in Banja Luka during the Bosnian War, the Sefer Bey mosque had likely been recently reconstructed.

BBC reported that in 2010, unspecified actors demolished a masjid in Livno. Bosnian Muslims also came under attack for attempting to reconstruct the Curcinica mosque in Livno. Such attacks have been understood as attempts to prevent the reacclimation of Bosnian Muslims in majority-Croat areas.

BBC reported that on October 17, 2011, unspecified actors damaged a Serb Orthodox cemetery in Mostar, desecrating tombstones. Mostar is dominated by Bosnian Muslims and Croats and was the site of fighting between Bosnian Serbs, Muslims, and Croats during the war.

BCC reported that on November 22, 2011, unspecified actors vandalized a mosque in Janja. Located in a Serb-dominated part of Bosnia, Janja was ethnically cleansed of non-Serb populations as a Serb-held territory during the Bosnian War.

BBC reported that between December 10-12, 2011, unspecified actors desecrated a mosque in Bosanski Novi, marking it with nationalist graffiti. The town is located in Republika Srpska and was the site of ethnic cleansing against non-Serbs during the Bosnian War.

BBC reported that on December 14, 2011, vandals desecrated a mosque in Mostar. Mostar is dominated by Bosnian Muslims and Croats. Tensions persisted in post-war Mostar regarding the reconstruction of a mosque in the Croat section of the city.

BBC reported that between February 29, 2012, and March 14, 2012, unspecified actors desecrated the Sefer Bey mosque in Banja Luka. An attack on the mosque also occurred in the Serb-dominated area in September 2011.

Reuters News reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 31, 1992, unspecified actors burned down a Catholic church in Stup. The church was located on the front confrontation line of the war, during the Siege of Sarajevo.

BBC reported that between April 1-7, 2012, vandals attacked a mosque in Banja Luka. The attack occurred during prayer time. A majority of the Serb-dominated area’s mosques were destroyed by Serb forces during the Bosnian War.

BBC reported that between June 7-14, 2012, unspecified actors desecrated three Serb graves in the Srebrenica area. Srebrenica was the sight of the 1995 massacre of approximately 8,000 Bosnian Muslim men and expulsion of Bosnian Muslim women and children by Bosnian Serb forces.

BBC reported that between July 30, 2012 and August 1, 2012 vandals threw a glass bottle at a mosque in Derventa. The now Serb-dominated town was the site of ethnic cleansing against non-Serb populations during the Bosnian War.

Transitions Online reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, Bosnian Serb forces destroyed the Turhan Beg Mosque in Ustikolina. When the mosque was rebuilt in 2007, its minaret was designed to be double the size of the original so that it could be seen from the nearby border with the Republika Srpska.

BBC reported that between August 5-10, 2012, unspecified actors desecrated several tombstones at Ilijas Orthodox cemetery near Sarajevo. The cemetery is located in the Sarajevo canton of the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina, which is dominated by Bosnian Muslims.

BBC reported that between September 21, 2012 and October 6, 2012, unspecified actors vandalized a mosque in Bijeljina. Bijeljina was the site of the massacre and expulsion of non-Serb populations during the Bosnian War, as well as the destruction of mosques.

BBC reported that between October 6-17, 2012, Turkish tourists broke down the door of the Serb Orthodox churchof the Assumption of the Most Holy Theotokos in Bratunac. The town is located in the Republika Srpska.

M2 Presswire reported that between July 11-31, 1995, Bosnian Serb forces demolished a mosque in Zepa. The perpetrators also expelled the Muslim population from their enclave in the Serb-dominated area and destroyed their homes.

Agence France-Presse reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 31, 2012, unspecified actors fired at and vandalized the Serb Orthodox church of the Transfiguration of the Holy Father Nikolai in Reljevo. The policeman assigned to guard the church was shot and killed in the Muslim-dominated village.

properties.sitename: Mostar Monument to B-H Army Soliders
properties.description: BBC reported that between January 6-15, 2013, unspecified actors destroyed a monument to the soldiers of Bosnia and Herzegovina in an explosion in Mostar. The attack was reportedly an act of terrorism that heightened tensions in the city.

HINA reported that between March 5-12, 2013, unspecified actors vandalized the Catholic church of the Holy Spirit near Fojnica, smashing its windows. The Croat-minority church had reportedly been desecrated before.

HINA reported that between March 28-29, 2013, unspecified actors set fire to the door of a Catholic church in Petricevac. Petricevac is located in the Serb-dominated Banja Luka district. The event occurred on Good Friday, an important Catholic holy day.

BBC reported that on August 11, 2006, unspecified actors bombed the grave of Alija Izetbegovic in Sarajevo. Izetbegovic was the first President of the Presidency of the Republic of Bosnia and Herzegovina and supported Bosnian independence from Yugoslavia in 1992.

HINA reported that between October 4-5, 2013, unspecified actors desecrated a Catholic church in Zenica, smashing windows and damaging the door. The perpetrators also damaged the plaque identifying the church as a cultural monument. The attack occurred on an important feast day.

HINA reported that between January 5-12, 2014, unspecified actors desecrated a Catholic cemetery in Tuzla. The Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina reportedly had not taken adequate measures to prevent the vandalization of Croat religious sites.

HINA reported that on January 12, 2014, unspecified actors burglarized the rectory and Catholic church in Ljubija. The Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina reportedly had not taken adequate measures to prevent the vandalization of Croat religious sites.

properties.sitename: State Archives of Bosnia and Herzegovina
properties.description: The Guardian reported that on February 8, 2014, anti-government protesters set the State Archives of Bosnia and Herzegovina on fire. Many of the archives important materials, including documents from the Ottoman period and World War II war crimes commission, were destroyed.

BBC reported that between February 8-13, 2014, protesters destroyed Catholic religious objects in the Croatian Democratic Union in Mostar. The protesters destroyed statues of the Virgin Mary, crucifixes, and ethnic insignia.

properties.sitename: Visegrad memorial to Bosniak genocide victims
properties.description: The Guardian reported that on January 23, 2014, Serb authorities censored the memorial to genocide victims in Visegrad. The authorities ordered that the word “genocide” be removed from the memorial in continued denial of crimes committed against Bosnian Muslims during the Bosnian War.

HINA reported that on July 25, 1992, Serb units demolished the Catholic church in Brisevo. The Serbs also killed or detained members of the local Croat population and burned down their homes and property.

BBC reported that between December 14, 1995 and August 1, 2014, unspecified actors desecrated the Serb cemetery in Gornja. The destruction of gravestones at the cemetery reportedly occurred in tandem with seizures of Serb property in the area.

The Winnipeg Free Press reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 14, 1995, unspecified actors destroyed the old city library in Mostar. The town was a site of sustained fighting between Bosnian Muslims, Croats, and Serbs during the Bosnian War.

HINA reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 31, 1992, Serb red berets destroyed a mosque in Doboj. The Serb paramilitary units also killed, tortured, and detained several civilians in the predominantly Muslim city.
The Christian Science Monitor reported that in August 1993, Serb forces set the Mt. Igman sporting facilities on fire. These facilities were used during the 1984 Sarajevo Olympic Games.

The Christian Science Monitor reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 31, 1992, Serb and Muslim forces damaged the Trebevic bobsled and luge facilities in Sarajevo. The facilities were damaged in clashes over the strategic high ground area.

The Globe and Mail reported that between April 6, 1992 and November 16, 1993, Bosnian Serb forces destroyed the Aladza mosque in Foca.  During the war, Foca was a Serb stronghold from which Bosnian Muslims populations fled or were expelled.

The Wall Street Journal reported that between April 6, 1992 and November 22, 1993, Muslims levelled 56 Orthodox churches in Tuzla. Tuzla was occupied by Bosnian Muslims. Serbs are associated with Christian orthodoxy.

properties.sitename: Mostar Serbian Orthodox monastery (Благовештење пресвете вогородице)
properties.description: The Wall Street Journal reported that between April 6, 1992 and November 22, 1993, Croats destroyed the Zitomislic Christian Orthodox monastery in Mostar. The monastic buildings were dynamited and bulldozed, and the library’s 16th and 17th century manuscript collection was damaged. Serbs are traditionally associated with Christian orthodoxy.

The St. Petersburg Times reported that between April 6, 1992 and October 9, 1993, Serb forces damaged most of the 72 mosques in Sarajevo. Mosques in most areas controlled by Serbs have reportedly been dynamited or demolished.

The Globe and Mail reported that on November 9, 1993, Croat forces destroyed the Stari Most in Mostar with tank fire. According to historians, the bridge symbolized unity between Croat and Muslim cultures.

The New York Times reported that in 1993, Bosnian Muslims partly destroyed a Catholic church in Podbrezje. The population of Podbrezje is majority Croat. Fighting occurred in the town between Bosnian Muslims and Croats.

The Orange County Register reported that on April 2, 1995, unspecified actors opened fire on a Roman Catholic church in Sarajevo. Peacekeeper supply routes into the city reportedly came under Serb gunfire the previous day. Serbs had not yet accepted an international peace plan.

Agence France-Presse reported that on April 6, 1995, Bosnian Serb forces fired a shell into a mosque courtyard in Hrasnica. The town center was also struck by shells. Fighting between Bosnian Serbs and Muslims continued as Serbs refused to accept a partition plan.

The Globe and Mail reported that between April 6, 1992 and November 16, 1993, Serb forces destroyed the Talih mosque in Banja Luka. Serb forces levelled all 16 of the predominantly-Serb city’s mosques and often bulldozed the sites of debris.

The Globe and Mail reported that between April 6, 1992 and November 16, 1993, Serb forces destroyed the Stupnicka mosque in Banja Luka. Serb forces levelled all 16 of the predominantly-Serb city’s mosques and often bulldozed the sites of debris.
The Globe and Mail reported that in December 1992, Muslim forces opened fire on a Serbian cemetery in Bjelovac. They sought to overrun the majority-Serb population in the town.

The Independent reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 18, 1992, Serb forces partly tore off the roof of the Mehmed Pasha mosque in Mostar with gunfire. The mosque dates to the 17th century.

The Independent reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 18, 1992, Serb forces damaged the Turkish towers on the sides of the Stari Most in Mostar with artillery fire. Pieces of masonry were ripped off of the 17th and 18th century towers, relics of the Ottoman empire.

The Independent reported that between April 6, 1992 and December 18, 1992, Serb forces damaged the Stari Most in Mostar with artillery fire. The northern parapet was destroyed and the entire bridge was scarred with bullet holes. The Islamic-style bridge links Muslim and Croat communities in Mostar.

Reuters News reported that on September 8, 1993, Serb radicals blew up a mosque in Banja Luka. The mosque was one of the final two mosques in the city, the other 14 already having been destroyed. Banja Luka was a Serb nationalist stronghold.
